# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: timeline-viz
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:timeline-viz/chronology] It is also a part of the discipline of history including earth history, the earth sciences, and study of the geologic time scale.
[src:timeline-viz/chronology] Chronology is the science of locating historical events in time.
[src:timeline-viz/chronology] It relies mostly upon chronometry, which is also known as timekeeping, and historiography, which examines the writing of history and the use of historical methods.
[src:timeline-viz/chronology] Radiocarbon dating estimates the age of formerly living things by measuring the proportion of carbon-14 isotope in their carbon content.
[src:timeline-viz/chronology] Dendrochronology estimates the age of trees by correlation of the various growth rings in their wood to known year-by-year reference sequences in the region to reflect year-to-year climatic variation.
[src:timeline-viz/chronology] Dendrochronology is used in turn as a calibration reference for radiocarbon dating curves.
[src:timeline-viz/chronology] The familiar terms *calendar* and *era* (within the meaning of a coherent system of numbered calendar years) concern two complementary fundamental concepts of chronology.
[src:timeline-viz/chronology] For example, during eight centuries the calendar belonging to the Christian era, which era was taken in use in the 8th century by Bede, was the Julian calendar, but after the year 1582 it was the Gregorian calendar.
[src:timeline-viz/chronology] Dionysius Exiguus (about the year 500) was the founder of that era, which is nowadays the most widespread dating system on earth.
[src:timeline-viz/chronology] An epoch is the date (year usually) when an era begins.
[src:timeline-viz/chronology] It was used systematically for the first time only about the year 400, by the Iberian historian Orosius.
[src:timeline-viz/chronology] Pope Boniface IV, in about the year 600, seems to have been the first who made a connection between this era and Anno Domini.
[src:timeline-viz/chronology] Dionysius Exiguus' Anno Domini era (which contains only calendar years *AD*) was extended by Bede to the complete Christian era (which contains, in addition all calendar years *BC*, but no *year zero*).
[src:timeline-viz/chronology] While of critical importance to the historian, methods of determining chronology are used in most disciplines of science, especially astronomy, geology, paleontology and archaeology.
[src:timeline-viz/chronology] In the absence of written history, with its chronicles and king lists, late 19th century archaeologists found that they could develop relative chronologies based on pottery techniques and styles.
[src:timeline-viz/chronology] In the field of Egyptology, William Flinders Petrie pioneered sequence dating to penetrate pre-dynastic Neolithic times, using groups of contemporary artefacts deposited together at a single time in graves and working backwards methodically from the earliest historical phases of Egypt.
[src:timeline-viz/chronology] This method of dating is known as seriation.
[src:timeline-viz/chronology] Known wares discovered at strata in sometimes quite distant sites, the product of trade, helped extend the network of chronologies.
[src:timeline-viz/chronology] Some cultures have retained the name applied to them in reference to characteristic forms, for lack of an idea of what they called themselves: "The Beaker People" in northern Europe during the 3rd millennium BCE, for example.
[src:timeline-viz/chronology] Laboratory techniques developed particularly after mid-20th century helped constantly revise and refine the chronologies developed for specific cultural areas.
[src:timeline-viz/chronology] Unrelated dating methods help reinforce a chronology, an axiom of corroborative evidence.
[src:timeline-viz/chronology] Ideally, archaeological materials used for dating a site should complement each other and provide a means of cross-checking.
[src:timeline-viz/chronology] Conclusions drawn from just one unsupported technique are usually regarded as unreliable.
[src:timeline-viz/chronology] The fundamental problem of chronology is to synchronize events.
[src:timeline-viz/chronology] By synchronizing an event it becomes possible to relate it to the current time and to compare the event to other events.
[src:timeline-viz/chronology] Among historians, a typical need is to synchronize the reigns of kings and leaders in order to relate the history of one country or region to that of another.
[src:timeline-viz/chronology] For example, the Chronicon of Eusebius (325 A.D.) is one of the major works of historical synchronism.
[src:timeline-viz/chronology] The first contains narrative chronicles of nine different kingdoms: Chaldean, Assyrian, Median, Lydian, Persian, Hebrew, Greek, Peloponnesian, Asian, and Roman.
[src:timeline-viz/chronology] The second part is a long table synchronizing the events from each of the nine kingdoms in parallel columns.
[src:timeline-viz/chronology] By comparing the parallel columns, the reader can determine which events were contemporaneous, or how many years separated two different events.
[src:timeline-viz/chronology] To place all the events on the same time scale, Eusebius used an Anno Mundi (A.M.) era, meaning that events were dated from the supposed beginning of the world as computed from the Book of Genesis in the Hebrew Pentateuch.
[src:timeline-viz/chronology] According to the computation Eusebius used, this occurred in 5199 B.C.
[src:timeline-viz/chronology] The Chronicon of Eusebius was widely used in the medieval world to establish the dates and times of historical events.
[src:timeline-viz/chronology] Subsequent chronographers, such as George Syncellus (died circa 811), analyzed and elaborated on the Chronicon by comparing with other chronologies.
[src:timeline-viz/chronology] The last great chronographer was Joseph Justus Scaliger (1540-1609) who reconstructed the lost Chronicon and synchronized all of ancient history in his two major works, *De emendatione temporum* (1583) and *Thesaurus temporum* (1606).
[src:timeline-viz/chronology] Much of modern historical datings and chronology of the ancient world ultimately derives from these two works.
[src:timeline-viz/chronology] Scaliger invented the concept of the Julian Day which is still used as the standard unified scale of time for both historians and astronomers.
[src:timeline-viz/chronology] In addition to the literary methods of synchronism used by traditional chronographers such as Eusebius, Syncellus and Scaliger, it is possible to synchronize events by archaeological or astronomical means.
[src:timeline-viz/chronology] For example, the Eclipse of Thales, described in the first book of Herodotus can potentially be used to date the Lydian War because the eclipse took place during the middle of an important battle in that war.
[src:timeline-viz/chronology] Likewise, various eclipses and other astronomical events described in ancient records can be used to astronomically synchronize historical events.
[src:timeline-viz/chronology] Another method to synchronize events is the use of archaeological findings, such as pottery, to do sequence dating.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] In addition, **Narrative visualization** is a method that uses visual elements such as charts, graphs, maps and the like to convey data or information.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] This approach blends data analysis, storytelling, and visualization to present information through structured narrative flows- *using visuals not just to present statistics, but to tell a story through data*.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Its goal is to help people identify trends, patterns, and relationships in data through a compelling story-driven visual experience.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Emerging technologies like virtual, augmented and mixed reality have the potential to make information visualization more immersive, intuitive, interactive and easily manipulable and thus enhance the user's visual perception and cognition.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Effective data visualization is well-sourced, appropriately contextualized, and presented in a simple, uncluttered manner.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] The underlying data is accurate and up-to-date to ensure insights are reliable.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Graphical items are well-chosen and aesthetically appealing, with shapes, colors and other visual elements used deliberately in a meaningful and non-distracting manner.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] The visuals are accompanied by supporting texts.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Verbal and graphical components complement each other to ensure clear, quick and memorable understanding.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Effective information visualization is aware of the needs and expertise level of the target audience.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Data scientists, analysts and data mining specialists use data visualization to check data quality, find errors, unusual gaps, missing values, clean data, explore the structures and features of data, and assess outputs of data-driven models.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization can be part of *data storytelling*, where they are paired with a narrative structure, to contextualize the analyzed data and communicate insights gained from analyzing it to convince the audience into making a decision or taking action.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization is interdisciplinary, it incorporates principles found in descriptive statistics, visual communication, graphic design, cognitive science and, interactive computer graphics and human-computer interaction.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Since effective visualization requires design skills, statistical skills and computing skills, it is both an art and a science.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Visual analytics combines statistical data analysis, data and information visualization, and human analytical reasoning through interactive visual interfaces to help users reach conclusions, gain actionable insights and make informed decisions which are otherwise difficult for computers to do.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Research into how people read and misread types of visualizations helps to determine what types and features of visualizations are most understandable and effective.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Unintentionally poor or intentionally misleading and deceptive visualizations can function as powerful tools which disseminate misinformation, manipulate public perception and divert public opinion.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Thus data visualization literacy has become an important component of data and information literacy in the information age akin to the roles played by textual, mathematical and visual literacy in the past.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] The field of data and information visualization has emerged "from research in human–computer interaction, computer science, graphics, visual design, psychology, photography and business methods.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] It is increasingly applied as a critical component in scientific research, digital libraries, data mining, financial data analysis, market studies, manufacturing production control, and drug discovery".
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization presumes that "visual representations and interaction techniques take advantage of the human eye's broad bandwidth pathway into the mind to allow users to see, explore, and understand large amounts of information at once.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Data analysis is an indispensable part of all applied research and problem solving in industry.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Among these approaches, information visualization, or visual data analysis, is the most reliant on the cognitive skills of human analysts, and allows the discovery of unstructured actionable insights that are limited only by human imagination and creativity.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] The analyst does not have to learn any sophisticated methods to be able to interpret the visualizations of the data.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Information visualization is also a hypothesis generation scheme, which can be, and is typically followed by more analytical or formal analysis, such as statistical hypothesis testing.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] To communicate information clearly and efficiently, data visualization uses statistical graphics, plots, information graphics and other tools.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Numerical data may be encoded using dots, lines, or bars, to visually communicate a quantitative message.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Effective visualization helps users analyze and reason about data and evidence.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] It makes complex data more accessible, understandable, and usable, but can also be reductive.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Users may have particular analytical tasks, such as making comparisons or understanding causality, and the design principle of the graphic (i.e., showing comparisons or showing causality) follows the task.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Tables are generally used where users will look up a specific measurement, while charts of various types are used to show patterns or relationships in the data for one or more variables.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization refers to the techniques used to communicate data or information by encoding it as visual objects (e.g., points, lines, or bars) contained in graphics.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] The goal is to communicate information clearly and efficiently to users.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] It is one of the steps in data analysis or data science.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] According to Vitaly Friedman (2008) the "main goal of data visualization is to communicate information clearly and effectively through graphical means.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] It doesn't mean that data visualization needs to look boring to be functional or extremely sophisticated to look beautiful.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] To convey ideas effectively, both aesthetic form and functionality need to go hand in hand, providing insights into a rather sparse and complex data set by communicating its key aspects in a more intuitive way.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Yet designers often fail to achieve a balance between form and function, creating gorgeous data visualizations which fail to serve their main purpose — to communicate information".
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Wattenberg suggested that an ideal visualization should not only communicate clearly, but stimulate viewer engagement and attention.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization is closely related to information graphics, information visualization, scientific visualization, exploratory data analysis and statistical graphics.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] In the new millennium, data visualization has become an active area of research, teaching and development.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] (2002), it has united scientific and information visualization.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] In the commercial environment data visualization is often referred to as dashboards.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Infographics are another very common form of data visualization.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Edward Tufte has explained that users of information displays are executing particular *analytical tasks* such as making comparisons.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] The *design principle* of the information graphic should support the analytical task.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] As William Cleveland and Robert McGill show, different graphical elements accomplish this more or less effectively.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] For example, dot plots and bar charts outperform pie charts.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] In his 1983 book *The Visual Display of Quantitative Information*, Edward Tufte defines 'graphical displays' and principles for effective graphical display in the following passage: "Excellence in statistical graphics consists of complex ideas communicated with clarity, precision, and efficiency.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] For example, the Minard diagram shows the losses suffered by Napoleon's army in the 1812–1813 period.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Six variables are plotted: the size of the army, its location on a two-dimensional surface (x and y), time, the direction of movement, and temperature.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] The line width illustrates a comparison (size of the army at points in time), while the temperature axis suggests a cause of the change in army size.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] This multivariate display on a two-dimensional surface tells a story that can be grasped immediately while identifying the source data to build credibility.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Not applying these principles may result in misleading graphs, distorting the message, or supporting an erroneous conclusion.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] According to Tufte, chartjunk refers to the extraneous interior decoration of the graphic that does not enhance the message or gratuitous three-dimensional or perspective effects.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Needlessly separating the explanatory key from the image itself, requiring the eye to travel back and forth from the image to the key, is a form of "administrative debris." The ratio of "data to ink" should be maximized, erasing non-data ink where feasible.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] The Congressional Budget Office summarized several best practices for graphical displays in a June 2014 presentation.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] These included: a) Knowing your audience; b) Designing graphics that can stand alone outside the report's context; and c) Designing graphics that communicate the key messages in the report.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] For greatest efficiency and simplicity of design and user experience, this readability is enhanced through the use of bijective mapping in that design of the image elements - where the mapping of representational element to data variable is unique.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Kosara (2007) also identifies the need for a visualisation to be "recognisable as a visualisation and not appear to be something else".
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] He also states that recognisability and readability may not always be required in all types of visualisation e.g.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] "informative art" (which would still meet all three above criteria but might not look like a visualisation) or "artistic visualisation" (which similarly is still based on non-visual data to create an image, but may not be readable or recognisable).
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Ranking: Categorical subdivisions are ranked in ascending or descending order, such as a ranking of sales performance (the *measure*) by sales persons (the *category*, with each sales person a *categorical subdivision*) during a single period.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart may be used to show the comparison across the sales persons.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Part-to-whole: Categorical subdivisions are measured as a ratio to the whole (i.e., a percentage out of 100%).
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] A pie chart or bar chart can show the comparison of ratios, such as the market share represented by competitors in a market.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Deviation: Categorical subdivisions are compared against a reference, such as a comparison of actual vs. budget expenses for several departments of a business for a given time period.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart can show comparison of the actual versus the reference amount.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Frequency distribution: Shows the number of observations of a particular variable for given interval, such as the number of years in which the stock market return is between intervals such as 0–10%, 11–20%, etc.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] A histogram, a type of bar chart, may be used for this analysis.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] A boxplot helps visualize key statistics about the distribution, such as median, quartiles, outliers, etc.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Correlation: Comparison between observations represented by two variables (X,Y) to determine if they tend to move in the same or opposite directions.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] For example, plotting unemployment (X) and inflation (Y) for a sample of months.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] A scatter plot is typically used for this message.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Nominal comparison: Comparing categorical subdivisions in no particular order, such as the sales volume by product code.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart may be used for this comparison.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Geographic or geospatial: Comparison of a variable across a map or layout, such as the unemployment rate by state or the number of persons on the various floors of a building.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Analysts reviewing a set of data may consider whether some or all of the messages and graphic types above are applicable to their task and audience.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] The process of trial and error to identify meaningful relationships and messages in the data is part of exploratory data analysis.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] A human can distinguish differences in line length, shape, orientation, distances, and color (hue) readily without significant processing effort; these are referred to as "pre-attentive attributes".
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] For example, it may require significant time and effort ("attentive processing") to identify the number of times the digit "5" appears in a series of numbers; but if that digit is different in size, orientation, or color, instances of the digit can be noted quickly through pre-attentive processing.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Compelling graphics take advantage of pre-attentive processing and attributes and the relative strength of these attributes.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] For example, since humans can more easily process differences in line length than surface area, it may be more effective to use a bar chart (which takes advantage of line length to show comparison) rather than pie charts (which use surface area to show comparison).
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Almost all data visualizations are created for human consumption.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Knowledge of human perception and cognition is necessary when designing intuitive visualizations.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Cognition refers to processes in human beings like perception, attention, learning, memory, thought, concept formation, reading, and problem solving.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Human visual processing is efficient in detecting changes and making comparisons between quantities, sizes, shapes and variations in lightness.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] When properties of symbolic data are mapped to visual properties, humans can browse through large amounts of data efficiently.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] It is estimated that 2/3 of the brain's neurons can be involved in visual processing.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Proper visualization provides a different approach to show potential connections, relationships, etc. which are not as obvious in non-visualized quantitative data.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Visualization can become a means of data exploration.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Studies have shown individuals used on average 19% less cognitive resources, and 4.5% better able to recall details when comparing data visualization with text.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] There is no comprehensive history of data visualization.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] There are no accounts that span the entire development of visual thinking and visual representation of data, and which collate the contributions of disparate disciplines.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Michael Friendly and Daniel Denis of York University are engaged in a project that attempts to provide a comprehensive history of visualization.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization is not a modern development.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Since prehistory, stellar data, or information such as location of stars were visualized on the walls of caves (such as those found in Lascaux Cave in Southern France) since the Pleistocene era.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Physical artefacts such as Mesopotamian clay tokens (5500 BC), Inca quipus (2600 BC) and Marshall Islands stick charts (n.d.) can also be considered as visualizing quantitative information.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] The first documented data visualization can be tracked back to 1160 B.C. with the Turin Papyrus Map which accurately illustrates the distribution of geological resources and provides information about quarrying of those resources.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Such maps can be categorized as thematic cartography, which is a type of data visualization that presents and communicates specific data and information through a geographical illustration designed to show a particular theme connected with a specific geographic area.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Earliest documented forms of data visualization were various thematic maps from different cultures and ideograms and hieroglyphs that provided and allowed interpretation of information illustrated.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] For example, Linear B tablets of Mycenae provided a visualization of information regarding Late Bronze Age era trades in the Mediterranean.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] The idea of coordinates was used by ancient Egyptian surveyors in laying out towns, earthly and heavenly positions were located by something akin to latitude and longitude at least by 200 BC, and the map projection of a spherical Earth into latitude and longitude by Claudius Ptolemy [c.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] 165] in Alexandria would serve as reference standards until the 14th century.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] The invention of paper and parchment allowed further development of visualizations.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] One graph from the 10th or possibly 11th century is an illustration of planetary movements, used in an appendix of a textbook in monastery schools.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] The graph apparently was meant to represent a plot of the inclinations of the planetary orbits as a function of the time.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] For this purpose, the zone of the zodiac was represented on a plane with a horizontal line divided into thirty parts as the time or longitudinal axis.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] The vertical axis designates the width of the zodiac.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] The horizontal scale appears to have been chosen for each planet individually for the periods cannot be reconciled.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] The accompanying text refers only to the amplitudes.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] The curves are apparently not related in time.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] By the 16th century, techniques and instruments for precise observation and measurement of physical quantities, and geographic and celestial position were well-developed (for example, a "wall quadrant" constructed by Tycho Brahe [1546–1601], covering an entire wall in his observatory).
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Particularly important were the development of triangulation and other methods to determine mapping locations accurately.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Very early, the measure of time led scholars to develop innovative way of visualizing the data (e.g.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Lorenz Codomann in 1596, Johannes Temporarius in 1596).
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Mathematicians René Descartes and Pierre de Fermat developed analytic geometry and two-dimensional coordinate system which heavily influenced the practical methods of displaying and calculating values.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Fermat and Blaise Pascal's work on statistics and probability theory laid the groundwork for what we now conceptualize as data.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] These developments helped William Playfair, who saw potential for graphical communication of quantitative data, to generate and develop graphical methods of statistics.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] In 1786, Playfair published the first presentation graphics.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] In the second half of the 20th century, Jacques Bertin used quantitative graphs to represent information "intuitively, clearly, accurately, and efficiently".
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] John Tukey and Edward Tufte pushed the bounds of data visualization; Tukey with his new statistical approach of exploratory data analysis and Tufte with his book "The Visual Display of Quantitative Information" paved the way for refining data visualization techniques for more than statisticians.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] With the progression of technology came the progression of data visualization; starting with hand-drawn visualizations and evolving into more technical applications – including interactive designs leading to software visualization.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] The modern study of visualization started with computer graphics, which "has from its beginning been used to study scientific problems.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] However, in its early days the lack of graphics power often limited its usefulness.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] The recent emphasis on visualization started in 1987 with the special issue of Computer Graphics on Visualization in *Scientific Computing*.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Since then there have been several conferences and workshops, co-sponsored by the IEEE Computer Society and ACM SIGGRAPH".
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] They have been devoted to the general topics of data visualization, information visualization and scientific visualization, and more specific areas such as volume visualization.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Programs like SAS, SOFA, R, Minitab, Cornerstone and more allow for data visualization in the field of statistics.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Other data visualization applications, more focused and unique to individuals, programming languages such as D3, Python (through matplotlib, seaborn) and JavaScript and Java(through JavaFX) help to make the visualization of quantitative data a possibility.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Private schools have also developed programs to meet the demand for learning data visualization and associated programming libraries, including free programs like The Data Incubator or paid programs like General Assembly.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Beginning with the symposium "Data to Discovery" in 2013, ArtCenter College of Design, Caltech and JPL in Pasadena have run an annual program on interactive data visualization.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] The program asks: How can interactive data visualization help scientists and engineers explore their data more effectively?
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] How can computing, design, and design thinking help maximize research results?
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] What methodologies are most effective for leveraging knowledge from these fields?
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] In recent years, with the increasing popularity of games, data and information visualization has been gradually applied in the gaming industry through the use of analytical tools to assess player statistics and game performance, which are visualized in the form of health points, maps, and diagrams.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] The data is then collected and stored by developers.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] The implementation of these tools in gaming assists developers in improving user experience and in the development and updating of newer games.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization involves specific terminology, some of which is derived from statistics.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] The distinction between quantitative and categorical variables is important because the two types require different methods of visualization.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Two primary types of information displays are tables and graphs.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Eppler and Lengler have developed the "Periodic Table of Visualization Methods," an interactive chart displaying various data visualization methods.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] It includes six types of data visualization methods: data, information, concept, strategy, metaphor and compound.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Interactive data visualization has been a pursuit of statisticians since the late 1960s.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Examples of the developments can be found on the American Statistical Association video lending library.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] There are different approaches on the scope of data visualization.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] One common focus is on information presentation, such as Friedman (2008).
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Friendly (2008) presumes two main parts of data visualization: statistical graphics, and thematic cartography.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] All these subjects are closely related to graphic design and information representation.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Within The Harvard Business Review, Scott Berinato developed a framework to approach data visualisation.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] To start thinking visually, users must consider two questions; 1) What you have and 2) what you're doing.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] The first step is identifying what data you want visualised.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] It is data-driven like profit over the past ten years or a conceptual idea like how a specific organisation is structured.
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Once this question is answered one can then focus on whether they are trying to communicate information (declarative visualisation) or trying to figure something out (exploratory visualisation).
[src:timeline-viz/data-visualization-p01] Scott Berinato combines these questions to give four types of visual communication that each have their own goals.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] A **Gantt chart** is a bar chart that illustrates a project schedule.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] It was designed and popularized by Henry Gantt c.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] Modern Gantt charts also show the dependency relationships between activities and the current schedule status.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] A Gantt chart is a type of bar chart that illustrates a project schedule.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] This chart lists the tasks to be performed on the vertical axis, and time intervals on the horizontal axis.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] The width of the horizontal bars in the graph shows the duration of each activity.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] Gantt charts illustrate the start and finish dates of the terminal elements and summary elements of a project.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] Terminal elements and summary elements constitute the work breakdown structure of the project.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] Modern Gantt charts also show the dependency (i.e., precedence network) relationships between activities.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] Gantt charts can be used to show current schedule status using percent-complete shadings and a vertical "TODAY" line.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] Gantt charts are sometimes equated with bar charts.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] Gantt charts are usually created initially using an *early start time approach*, where each task is scheduled to start immediately when its prerequisites are complete.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] This method maximizes the float time available for all tasks.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] Widely used in project planning in the present day, Gantt charts were considered revolutionary when introduced.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] The first known tool of this type was developed in 1896 by Karol Adamiecki, who called it a *harmonogram*.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] Adamiecki, however, published his chart only in Russian and Polish which limited both its adoption and recognition of his authorship.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] In 1912, Hermann Schürch published what could be considered Gantt charts while discussing a construction project.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] Charts of the type published by Schürch appear to have been in common use in Germany at the time; however, the prior development leading to Schürch's work is unclear.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] Unlike later Gantt charts, Schürch's charts did not display interdependencies, leaving them to be inferred by the reader.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] These were also static representations of a planned schedule.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] The chart is named after Henry Gantt (1861–1919), who designed his chart around the years 1910–1915.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] Gantt originally created his tool for systematic, routine operations.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] He designed this visualization tool to more easily measure productivity levels of employees and gauge which employees were under- or over-performing.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] Gantt also frequently included graphics and other visual indicators in his charts to track performance.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] One of the first major applications of Gantt charts was by the United States during World War I, at the instigation of General William Crozier.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] The earliest Gantt charts were drawn on paper and therefore had to be redrawn entirely in order to adjust to schedule changes.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] For many years, project managers used pieces of paper or blocks for Gantt chart bars so they could be adjusted as needed.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] Gantt's collaborator Walter Polakov introduced Gantt charts to the Soviet Union in 1929 when he was working for the Supreme Soviet of the National Economy.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] They were used in developing the First Five Year Plan, supplying Russian translations to explain their use.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] In the 1980s, personal computers allowed widespread creation of complex and elaborate Gantt charts.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] The first desktop applications were intended mainly for project managers and project schedulers.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] With the advent of the Internet and increased collaboration over networks at the end of the 1990s, Gantt charts became a common feature of web-based applications, including collaborative groupware..
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] By 2012, almost all Gantt charts were made by software which can easily adjust to schedule changes.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] In 1999, Gantt charts were identified as "one of the most widely used management tools for project scheduling and control".
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] In the following tables there are seven tasks, labeled *a* through *g*.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] Some tasks can be done concurrently (*a* and *b*) while others cannot be done until their predecessor task is complete (*c* and *d* cannot begin until *a* is complete).
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] Additionally, each task has three time estimates: the optimistic time estimate (*O*), the most likely or normal time estimate (*M*), and the pessimistic time estimate (*P*).
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] The expected time (*TE*) is estimated using the beta probability distribution for the time estimates, using the formula (*O* + 4*M* + *P*) ÷ 6.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] Once this step is complete, one can draw a Gantt chart or a network diagram.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] In a progress Gantt chart, tasks are shaded in proportion to the degree of their completion: a task that is 60% complete would be 60% shaded, starting from the left.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] A vertical line is drawn at the time index when the progress Gantt chart is created, and this line can then be compared with shaded tasks.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] If everything is on schedule, all task portions left of the line will be shaded, and all task portions right of the line will not be shaded.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] This provides a visual representation of how the project and its tasks are ahead or behind schedule.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] Linked Gantt charts contain lines indicating the dependencies between tasks.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] However, linked Gantt charts quickly become cluttered in all but the simplest cases.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] Critical path network diagrams are superior to visually communicate the relationships between tasks.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] Nevertheless, Gantt charts are often preferred over network diagrams because Gantt charts are easily interpreted without training, whereas critical path diagrams require training to interpret.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] Gantt chart software typically provides mechanisms to link task dependencies, although this data may or may not be visually represented.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] Gantt charts and network diagrams are often used for the same project, both being generated from the same data by a software application.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] The Gantt chart's widespread adoption is perhaps less based on its universal application and suitability as perhaps the absence of any alternative.
[src:timeline-viz/gantt-chart] It flattens assumptions, which in turn can constrain the ability to respond to uncertainty and change.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Infographics have been around for many years and recently the increase of the number of easy-to-use, free tools have made the creation of infographics available to a large segment of the population.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Social media sites such as Facebook and Twitter have also allowed for individual infographics to be spread among many people around the world.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Infographics are widely used in the age of short attention span.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] In newspapers, infographics are commonly used to show the weather, as well as maps, site plans, and graphs for summaries of data.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Some books are almost entirely made up of information graphics, such as David Macaulay's *The Way Things Work*.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] The Snapshots in *USA Today* are also an example of simple infographics used to convey news and current events.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Modern maps, especially route maps for transit systems, use infographic techniques to integrate a variety of information, such as the conceptual layout of the transit network, transfer points, and local landmarks.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Public transportation maps, such as those for the Washington Metro and the London Underground map, are well-known infographics.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Public places such as transit terminals usually have some sort of integrated "signage system" with standardized icons and stylized maps.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] In 1626, Christoph Scheiner published the *Rosa Ursina sive Sol*, a book that revealed his research about the rotation of the sun.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Infographics appeared in the form of illustrations demonstrating the Sun's rotation patterns.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] In 1786, William Playfair, an engineer and political economist, published the first data graphs in his book *The Commercial and Political Atlas*.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] To represent the economy of 18th century England, Playfair used statistical graphs, bar charts, line graphs, area charts, and histograms.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] In his work, *Statistical Breviary*, he is credited with introducing the first pie chart.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Around 1820, modern geography was established by Carl Ritter.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] His maps included shared frames, agreed map legends, scales, repeatability, and fidelity.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Such a map can be considered a "supersign" which combines sign systems—as defined by Charles Sanders Peirce—consisting of symbols, icons, indexes as representations.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Other examples can be seen in the works of geographers Ritter and Alexander von Humboldt.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] In 1857, English nurse Florence Nightingale used information graphics to persuade Queen Victoria to improve conditions in military hospitals.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] The principal one she used was the Coxcomb chart, a combination of stacked bar and pie charts, depicting the number and causes of deaths during each month of the Crimean War.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] 1861 saw the release of an influential information graphic on the subject of Napoleon's disastrous march on Moscow.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] James Joseph Sylvester introduced the term "graph" in 1878 in the scientific magazine *Nature* and published a set of diagrams showing the relationship between chemical bonds and mathematical properties.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] These were also some of the first mathematical graphs.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] In 1900, the African-American historian, sociologist, writer, and Black rights activist, W.E.B.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Du Bois presented data visualizations at the Exposition Universelle (1900) in Paris, France.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] In addition to curating 500 photographs of the lives of Black Americans, Du Bois and his Atlanta University team of students and scholars created 60 handmade data visualizations to document the ways Black Americans were being denied access to education, housing, employment, and household wealth.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] The Cologne Progressives developed an aesthetic approach to art that focused on communicating information.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Gerd Arntz, Peter Alma and Augustin Tschinkel, all participants in this movement were recruited by Otto Neurath for the Gesellschafts- und Wirtschaftsmuseum, where they developed the Vienna Method from 1926 to 1934.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Here simple images were used to represent data in a structured way.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Following the victory of Austrofascism in the Austrian Civil War, the team moved to the Netherlands where they continued their work rebranding it Isotypes (International System of Typographic Picture Education).
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] The method was also applied by IZOSTAT (ИЗОСТАТ) in the Soviet Union.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] In 1942 Isidore Isou published the Lettrist manifesto, a document covering art, culture, poetry, film, and political theory.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] The included works also called metagraphics and hypergraphics, are a synthesis of writing and visual art.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] In 1958 Stephen Toulmin proposed a graphical argument model, called The Toulmin Model of Argumentation.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] The diagram contained six interrelated components used for analyzing arguments and was considered Toulmin's most influential work, particularly in the field of rhetoric, communication, and computer science.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] The Toulmin Model of Argumentation became influential in argumentation theory and its applications.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] In 1972 and 1973, respectively, the Pioneer 10 and Pioneer 11 spacecraft included on their vessels the Pioneer Plaques, a pair of gold-anodized aluminum plaques, each featuring a pictorial message.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] The pictorial messages included nude male and female figures as well as symbols that were intended to provide information about the origin of the spacecraft.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] The images were designed by Carl Sagan and Frank Drake and were unique in that their graphical meanings were to be understandable to extraterrestrial beings, who would have no conception of human language.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] A pioneer in data visualization, Edward Tufte, wrote a series of books – *Visual Explanations*, *The Visual Display of Quantitative Information*, and *Envisioning Information* – on the subject of information graphics.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Referred to by The New York Times as the "da Vinci of Data", Tufte began to give day-long lectures and workshops on the subject of infographics starting in 1993.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] As of 2012, Tufte still gives these lectures.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] To Tufte, good data visualizations represent every data point accurately and enable a viewer to see trends and patterns in the data.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Tufte's contribution to the field of data visualization and infographics is considered immense, and his design principles can be seen in many websites, magazines, and newspapers today.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] The infographics created by Peter Sullivan for The Sunday Times in the 1970s, 1980s, and 1990s were some of the key factors in encouraging newspapers to use more infographics.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Sullivan is also one of the few authors who have written about information graphics in newspapers.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Likewise, the staff artists at USA Today, the United States newspaper that debuted in 1982, established the goal of using graphics to make information easier to comprehend.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] However, the paper has received criticism for oversimplifying news stories and for creating infographics that some find emphasizes entertainment over content and data.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Tufte coined the term chartjunk to refer to graphics that are visually appealing to the point of losing the information contained within them.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] With vector graphics and raster graphics becoming ubiquitous in computing in the 21st century, data visualizations have been applied to commonly used computer systems, including desktop publishing and Geographic Information Systems (GIS).
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Closely related to the field of information graphics is information design, which is the creation of infographics.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] By the year 2000, Adobe Flash-based animations on the Internet had made use of many key practices in creating infographics in order to create a variety of products and games.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Likewise, television began to incorporate infographics into the viewers' experiences in the early 2000s.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] One example of infographics usage in television and in pop culture is the 2002 music video by the Norwegian musicians of Röyksopp, for their song "Remind Me." The video was composed entirely of animated infographics.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Similarly, in 2004, a television commercial for the French nuclear technology company Areva used animated infographics as an advertising tactic.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Both of these videos and the attention they received have conveyed to other fields the potential value of using information graphics to describe complex information efficiently.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] With the rise of alternatives to Adobe Flash, such as HTML 5 and CSS3, infographics are now created in a variety of media with a number of software tools.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] The field of journalism has also incorporated and applied information graphics to news stories.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] For stories that intend to include text, images, and graphics, the system called the maestro concept allows entire newsrooms to collaborate and organize a story to successfully incorporate all components.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Across many newsrooms, this teamwork-integrated system is applied to improve time management.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] The maestro system is designed to improve the presentation of stories for busy readers of media.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Many news-based websites have also used interactive information graphics in which the user can extract information on a subject as they explore the graphic.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Many businesses use infographics as a medium for communicating with and attracting potential customers.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Information graphics are a form of content marketing and have become a tool for internet marketers and companies to create content that others will link to, thus possibly boosting a company's reputation and online presence.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Religious denominations have also started using infographics.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] For example, The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints has made numerous infographics to help people learn about their faith, missionaries, temples, lay ministry, and family history efforts.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Infographics are finding a home in the classroom as well.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Courses that teach students to create their own infographics using a variety of tools may encourage engagement in the classroom and may lead to a better understanding of the concepts they are mapping onto the graphics.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] With the popularity of social media, infographics have become popular, often as static images or simple web interfaces, covering any number of topics.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Such infographics are often shared between users of social networks such as Facebook, Twitter, Pinterest, Google+ and Reddit.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] The hashtag #infographic was tweeted 56,765 times in March 2012 and at its peak 3,365 times in a span of 24 hours.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] The three parts of all infographics are the visual, the content, and the knowledge.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] The visual consists of colors and graphics.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] There are two different types of graphics – theme, and reference.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] These graphics are included in all infographics and represent the underlying visual representation of the data.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Reference graphics are generally icons that can be used to point to certain data, although they are not always found in infographics.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Statistics and facts usually serve as the content for infographics and can be obtained from any number of sources, including census data and news reports.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] One of the most important aspects of infographics is that they contain some sort of insight into the data that they are presenting – this is the knowledge.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Infographics are effective because of their visual element.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Humans receive input from all five of their senses (sight, touch, hearing, smell, taste), but they receive significantly more information from vision than any of the other four.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Fifty percent of the human brain is dedicated to visual functions, and images are processed faster than text.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] The brain processes pictures all at once, but processes text in a linear fashion, meaning it takes much longer to obtain information from text.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Entire business processes or industry sectors can be made relevant to a new audience through a guidance design technique that leads the eye.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] The page may link to a complete report, but the infographic primes the reader making the subject-matter more accessible.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Online trends, such as the increasingly short attention span of Internet users, has also contributed to the increasing popularity and effectiveness of infographics.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] When designing the visual aspect of an infographic, a number of considerations must be made to optimize the effectiveness of the visualization.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] The six components of visual encoding are spatial, marks, connection, enclosure, retinal properties, and temporal encoding.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Each of these can be utilized in its own way to represent relationships between different types of data.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] However, studies have shown that spatial position is the most effective way to represent numerical data and leads to the fastest and easiest understanding by viewers.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Therefore, the designers often spatially represent the most important relationship being depicted in an infographic.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] There are also three basic provisions of communication that need to be assessed when designing an infographic – appeal, comprehension, and retention.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] "Appeal" is the idea that communication needs to engage its audience.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Comprehension implies that the viewer should be able to easily understand the information that is presented to them.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] And finally, "retention" means that the viewer should remember the data presented by the infographic.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] The order of importance of these provisions depends on the purpose of the infographic.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] If the infographic is meant to convey information in an unbiased way, such as in the domains of academia or science, comprehension should be considered first, then retention, and finally, appeal.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] However, if the infographic is being used for commercial purposes, then appeal becomes most important, followed by retention and comprehension.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] When infographics are being used for editorial purposes, such as in a newspaper, the appeal is again most important but is followed first by comprehension and then retention.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] However, the appeal and the retention can in practice be put together with the aid of a comprehensible layout design.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Recently, as an attempt to study the effect of the layout of an infographic on the comprehension of the viewers, a new Neural Network-based cognitive load estimation method was applied on different types of common layouts for the infographic design.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] When the varieties of factors listed above are taken into consideration when designing infographics, they can be a highly efficient and effective way to convey large amounts of information in a visual manner.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Data visualizations are often used in infographics and may make up the entire infographic.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] There are many types of visualizations that can be used to represent the same set of data.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Therefore, it is crucial to identify the appropriate visualization for the data set and infographic by taking into consideration graphical features such as position, size, shape, and color.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] There are primarily five types of visualization categories – time-series data, statistical distributions, maps, hierarchies, and networking.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Time-series data is one of the most common forms of data visualization.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Examples of graphics in this category include index charts, stacked graphs, small multiples, and horizon graphs.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Index charts are ideal to use when raw values are less important than relative changes.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] It is an interactive line chart that shows percentage changes for a collection of time-series data based on a selected index point.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] For example, stock investors could use this because they are less concerned with the specific price and more concerned with the rate of growth.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Stacked graphs are area charts that are stacked on top of each other, and depict aggregate patterns.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] They allow viewers to see overall patterns and individual patterns.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] However, they do not support negative numbers and make it difficult to accurately interpret trends.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] An alternative to stacked graphs is small multiples.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Instead of stacking each area chart, each series is individually shown so the overall trends of each sector are more easily interpreted.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Horizon graphs are a space efficient method to increase the data density of a time-series while preserving resolution.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Statistical distributions reveal trends based on how numbers are distributed.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Common examples include histograms and box-and-whisker plots, which convey statistical features such as mean, median, and outliers.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] In addition to these common infographics, alternatives include stem-and-leaf plots, Q–Q plots, scatter plot matrices (SPLOM) and parallel coordinates.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] For assessing a collection of numbers and focusing on frequency distribution, stem-and-leaf plots can be helpful.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] The numbers are binned based on the first significant digit, and within each stack binned again based on the second significant digit.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] On the other hand, Q–Q plots compare two probability distributions by graphing quantiles against each other.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] This allows the viewer to see if the plot values are similar and if the two are linearly related.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] SPLOM is a technique that represents the relationships among multiple variables.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] It uses multiple scatter plots to represent a pairwise relation among variables.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Another statistical distribution approach to visualize multivariate data is parallel coordinates.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Rather than graphing every pair of variables in two dimensions, the data is repeatedly plotted on a parallel axis, and corresponding points are then connected with a line.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] The advantage of parallel coordinates is that they are relatively compact, allowing many variables to be shown simultaneously.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Maps are a natural way to represent geographical data.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Time and space can be depicted through the use of flow maps.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Line strokes are used with various widths and colors to help encode information.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Choropleth maps, which encode data through color and geographical region, are also commonly used.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Graduated symbol maps are another method to represent geographical data.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] They are an alternative to choropleth map and use symbols, such as pie charts for each area, over a map.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] This map allows for more dimensions to be represented using various shapes, sizes, and colors.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Cartograms, on the other hand, completely distort the shape of a region and directly encode a data variable.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Instead of using a geographic map, regions are redrawn proportionally to the data.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] For example, each region can be represented by a circle and the size/color is directly proportional to other information, such as population size.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Many data sets, such as spatial entities of countries or common structures for governments, can be organized into natural hierarchies.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Node-link diagrams, adjacency diagrams, and enclosure diagrams are all types of infographics that effectively communicate hierarchical data.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Node-link diagrams are a popular method due to the tidy and space-efficient results.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] A node-link diagram is similar to a tree, where each node branches off into multiple sub-sections.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] An alternative is adjacency diagrams, which is a space-filling variant of the node-link diagram.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Instead of drawing a link between hierarchies, nodes are drawn as solid areas with sub-sections inside of each section.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] This method allows for size to be easily represented than in the node-link diagrams.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Enclosure diagrams are also a space-filling visualization method.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] However, they use containment rather than adjacency to represent the hierarchy.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Similar to the adjacency diagram, the size of the node is easily represented in this model.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Network visualization explores relationships, such as friendships and cliques.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Three common types are force-directed layout, arc diagrams, and matrix view.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Force-directed layouts are a common and intuitive approach to network layout.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] In this system, nodes are similar to charged particles, which repel each other.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Links are used to pull related nodes together.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Arc diagrams are one-dimensional layouts of nodes with circular arcs linking each node.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] When used properly, with good order in nodes, cliques and bridges are easily identified in this layout.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Alternatively, mathematicians and computer scientists more often use matrix views.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Each value has an (x,y) value in the matrix that corresponds to a node.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] By using color and saturation instead of text, values associated with the links can be perceived rapidly.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] While this method makes it hard to view the path of the nodes, there are no line crossings, which in a large and highly connected network can quickly become too cluttered.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] While all of these visualizations can be effectively used on their own, many modern infographics combine multiple types into one graphic, along with other features, such as illustrations and text.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Some modern infographics do not even contain data visualization, and instead are simply a colorful and succinct ways to present knowledge.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Fifty-three percent of the 30 most-viewed infographics on the infographic sharing site visual.ly did not contain actual data.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Comparison infographics are a type of visual representation that focuses on comparing and contrasting different elements, such as products, services, options, or features.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] These infographics are designed to help viewers make informed decisions by presenting information in a clear and concise manner.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Comparison infographics can be highly effective in simplifying complex data and highlighting key differences between multiple items.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Infographics can be created by hand using simple everyday tools such as graph paper, pencils, markers, and rulers.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] However, today they are more often created using computer software, which is often both faster and easier.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] They can be created with general illustration software.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Diagrams can be manually created and drawn using software, which can be downloaded for the desktop or used online.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Templates can be used to get users started on their diagrams.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] Additionally, the software allows users to collaborate on diagrams in real time over the Internet.
[src:timeline-viz/infographic] There are also numerous tools to create very specific types of visualizations, such as creating a visualization based on embedded data in the photos on a user's smartphone.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] In mathematics, a **time series** is a sequence of data points indexed, listed, or graphed in chronological order.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Most commonly, a time series consists of observations recorded at successive equally spaced points in time.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Thus, it represents a form of discrete-time data.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] A time series may describe measurements collected over seconds, days, years, or even centuries.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Common examples include heights of ocean tides, counts of sunspots, daily temperature readings, and the closing values of stock market indices such as the Dow Jones Industrial Average.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] A time series is often visualized using a run chart (a type of temporal line chart), which helps identify patterns such as trends, seasonal effects, and irregular fluctuations.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Time series data have a natural temporal ordering.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] This makes time series analysis distinct from cross-sectional studies, in which there is no natural ordering of the observations (e.g. explaining people's wages by reference to their respective education levels, where the individuals' data could be entered in any order).
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Time series analysis is also distinct from spatial data analysis where the observations typically relate to geographical locations (e.g. accounting for house prices by the location as well as the intrinsic characteristics of the houses).
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] A stochastic model for a time series will generally reflect the fact that observations close together in time will be more closely related than observations further apart.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] In addition, time series models will often make use of the natural one-way ordering of time so that values for a given period will be expressed as deriving in some way from past values, rather than from future values (see time reversibility).
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Time series analysis can be applied to real-valued, continuous data, discrete numeric data, or discrete symbolic data (i.e. sequences of characters, such as letters and words in the English language).
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Methods for time series analysis may be divided into two classes: frequency-domain methods and time-domain methods.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] The former include spectral analysis and wavelet analysis; the latter include auto-correlation and cross-correlation analysis.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] In the time domain, correlation and analysis can be made in a filter-like manner using scaled correlation, thereby mitigating the need to operate in the frequency domain.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Additionally, time series analysis techniques may be divided into parametric and non-parametric methods.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] The parametric approaches assume that the underlying stationary stochastic process has a certain structure which can be described using a small number of parameters (for example, using an autoregressive or moving-average model).
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] In these approaches, the task is to estimate the parameters of the model that describes the stochastic process.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] By contrast, non-parametric approaches explicitly estimate the covariance or the spectrum of the process without assuming that the process has any particular structure.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Methods of time series analysis may also be divided into linear and non-linear, and univariate and multivariate.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] A time series is one type of panel data.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Panel data is the general class, a multidimensional data set, whereas a time series data set is a one-dimensional panel (as is a cross-sectional dataset).
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] A data set may exhibit characteristics of both panel data and time series data.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] One way to tell is to ask what makes one data record unique from the other records.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] If the answer is the time data field, then this is a time series data set candidate.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] If determining a unique record requires a time data field and an additional identifier which is unrelated to time (e.g. student ID, stock symbol, country code), then it is panel data candidate.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] If the differentiation lies on the non-time identifier, then the data set is a cross-sectional data set candidate.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] There are several types of motivation and data analysis available for time series which are appropriate for different purposes.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] In the context of statistics, econometrics, quantitative finance, seismology, meteorology, and geophysics the primary goal of time series analysis is forecasting.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] In the context of signal processing, control engineering and communication engineering it is used for signal detection.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Other applications are in data mining, pattern recognition and machine learning, where time series analysis can be used for clustering, classification, query by content, anomaly detection as well as forecasting.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] A simple way to examine a regular time series is manually with a line chart.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] The datagraphic shows tuberculosis deaths in the United States, along with the yearly change and the percentage change from year to year.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] The total number of deaths declined in every year until the mid-1980s, after which there were occasional increases, often proportionately - but not absolutely - quite large.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] A study of corporate data analysts found two challenges to exploratory time series analysis: discovering the shape of interesting patterns, and finding an explanation for these patterns.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Visual tools that represent time series data as heat map matrices can help overcome these challenges.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] This approach may be based on harmonic analysis and filtering of signals in the frequency domain using the Fourier transform, and spectral density estimation.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Its development was significantly accelerated during World War II by mathematician Norbert Wiener, electrical engineers Rudolf E.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Kálmán, Dennis Gabor and others for filtering signals from noise and predicting signal values at a certain point in time.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] An equivalent effect may be achieved in the time domain, as in a Kalman filter; see filtering and smoothing for more techniques.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Curve fitting is the process of constructing a curve, or mathematical function, that has the best fit to a series of data points, possibly subject to constraints.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Curve fitting can involve either interpolation, where an exact fit to the data is required, or smoothing, in which a "smooth" function is constructed that approximately fits the data.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] A related topic is regression analysis, which focuses more on questions of statistical inference such as how much uncertainty is present in a curve that is fit to data observed with random errors.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Fitted curves can be used as an aid for data visualization, to infer values of a function where no data are available, and to summarize the relationships among two or more variables.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Extrapolation refers to the use of a fitted curve beyond the range of the observed data, and is subject to a degree of uncertainty since it may reflect the method used to construct the curve as much as it reflects the observed data.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] For processes that are expected to generally grow in magnitude one of the curves in the graphic (and many others) can be fitted by estimating their parameters.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] The construction of economic time series involves the estimation of some components for some dates by interpolation between values ("benchmarks") for earlier and later dates.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Interpolation is estimation of an unknown quantity between two known quantities (historical data), or drawing conclusions about missing information from the available information ("reading between the lines").
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Interpolation is useful where the data surrounding the missing data is available and its trend, seasonality, and longer-term cycles are known.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] This is often done by using a related series known for all relevant dates.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Alternatively polynomial interpolation or spline interpolation is used where piecewise polynomial functions are fitted in time intervals such that they fit smoothly together.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] A different problem which is closely related to interpolation is the approximation of a complicated function by a simple function (also called regression).
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] The main difference between regression and interpolation is that polynomial regression gives a single polynomial that models the entire data set.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Spline interpolation, however, yield a piecewise continuous function composed of many polynomials to model the data set.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Extrapolation is the process of estimating, beyond the original observation range, the value of a variable on the basis of its relationship with another variable.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] It is similar to interpolation, which produces estimates between known observations, but extrapolation is subject to greater uncertainty and a higher risk of producing meaningless results.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] In general, a function approximation problem asks us to select a function among a well-defined class that closely matches ("approximates") a target function in a task-specific way.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Second, the target function, call it *g*, may be unknown; instead of an explicit formula, only a set of points (a time series) of the form (*x*, *g*(*x*)) is provided.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Depending on the structure of the domain and codomain of *g*, several techniques for approximating *g* may be applicable.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] For example, if *g* is an operation on the real numbers, techniques of interpolation, extrapolation, regression analysis, and curve fitting can be used.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] If the codomain (range or target set) of *g* is a finite set, one is dealing with a classification problem instead.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] A related problem of *online* time series approximation is to summarize the data in one-pass and construct an approximate representation that can support a variety of time series queries with bounds on worst-case error.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] To some extent, the different problems (regression, classification, fitness approximation) have received a unified treatment in statistical learning theory, where they are viewed as supervised learning problems.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] In statistics, prediction is a part of statistical inference.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] One particular approach to such inference is known as predictive inference, but the prediction can be undertaken within any of the several approaches to statistical inference.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Indeed, one description of statistics is that it provides a means of transferring knowledge about a sample of a population to the whole population, and to other related populations, which is not necessarily the same as prediction over time.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] When information is transferred across time, often to specific points in time, the process is known as forecasting.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Assigning time series pattern to a specific category, for example identify a word based on series of hand movements in sign language.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Splitting a time-series into a sequence of segments.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] It is often the case that a time-series can be represented as a sequence of individual segments, each with its own characteristic properties.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] For example, the audio signal from a conference call can be partitioned into pieces corresponding to the times during which each person was speaking.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] In time-series segmentation, the goal is to identify the segment boundary points in the time-series, and to characterize the dynamical properties associated with each segment.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] One can approach this problem using change-point detection, or by modeling the time-series as a more sophisticated system, such as a Markov jump linear system.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Time series data may be clustered, however special care has to be taken when considering subsequence clustering.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Subsequence time series clustering resulted in unstable (random) clusters *induced by the feature extraction* using chunking with sliding windows.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] It was found that the cluster centers (the average of the time series in a cluster - also a time series) follow an arbitrarily shifted sine pattern (regardless of the dataset, even on realizations of a random walk).
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] This means that the found cluster centers are non-descriptive for the dataset because the cluster centers are always nonrepresentative sine waves.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Models for time series data can have many forms and represent different stochastic processes.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] When modeling variations in the level of a process, three broad classes of practical importance are the *autoregressive* (AR) models, the *integrated* (I) models, and the *moving-average* (MA) models.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] These three classes depend *linearly* on previous data points.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Combinations of these ideas produce autoregressive moving-average (ARMA) and autoregressive integrated moving-average (ARIMA) models.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] The autoregressive fractionally integrated moving-average (ARFIMA) model generalizes the former three.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Another important generalization is the time-varying autoregressive (TVAR) model, in which the AR coefficients are allowed to change over time, enabling the model to capture evolving or non-stationary dynamics.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Extensions of these classes to deal with vector-valued data are available under the heading of multivariate time-series models and sometimes the preceding acronyms are extended by including an initial "V" for "vector", as in VAR for vector autoregression.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] For these models, the acronyms are extended with a final "X" for "exogenous".
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Time-varying autoregressive (TVAR) models are especially useful for analyzing non-stationary time series in which the underlying dynamics evolve over time in complex ways, not limited to classical forms of variation such as trends or seasonal patterns.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] This flexibility makes them well suited to modeling structural changes, regime shifts, or gradual evolutions in a system's behavior.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Estimation of TVAR models typically involves methods such as kernel smoothing, recursive least squares, or Kalman filtering.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Non-linear dependence of the level of a series on previous data points is of interest, partly because of the possibility of producing a chaotic time series.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] However, more importantly, empirical investigations can indicate the advantage of using predictions derived from non-linear models, over those from linear models, as for example in nonlinear autoregressive exogenous models.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Among other types of non-linear time series models, there are models to represent the changes of variance over time (heteroskedasticity).
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] These models represent autoregressive conditional heteroskedasticity (ARCH) and the collection comprises a wide variety of representation (GARCH, TARCH, EGARCH, FIGARCH, CGARCH, etc.).
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Here changes in variability are related to, or predicted by, recent past values of the observed series.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] This is in contrast to other possible representations of locally varying variability, where the variability might be modeled as being driven by a separate time-varying process, as in a doubly stochastic model.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Multiscale (often referred to as multiresolution) techniques decompose a given time series, attempting to illustrate time dependence at multiple scales.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] See also Markov switching multifractal (MSMF) techniques for modeling volatility evolution.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] A hidden Markov model (HMM) is a statistical Markov model in which the system being modeled is assumed to be a Markov process with unobserved (hidden) states.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] An HMM can be considered as the simplest dynamic Bayesian network.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] HMM models are widely used in speech recognition, for translating a time series of spoken words into text.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Many of these models are collected in the python package sktime.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] A number of different notations are in use for time-series analysis.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Ergodicity implies stationarity, but the converse is not necessarily the case.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Stationarity is usually classified into strict stationarity and wide-sense or second-order stationarity.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Both models and applications can be developed under each of these conditions, although the models in the latter case might be considered as only partly specified.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] In addition, time-series analysis can be applied where the series are seasonally stationary or non-stationary.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Situations where the amplitudes of frequency components change with time can be dealt with in time-frequency analysis which makes use of a time–frequency representation of a time-series or signal.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Time series can be visualized with two categories of chart: Overlapping Charts and Separated Charts.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] Jevons was the first to study times series.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] In his book he examined a number of weekly financial time series between the years 1825 to 1860 inclusive.
[src:timeline-viz/time-series] These included times series of bankruptcies, currency circulation and discount rates.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] A **timeline** is a list of events displayed in chronological order.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] It is typically a graphic design showing a long bar labelled with dates paralleling it, and usually contemporaneous events.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] Timelines can use any suitable scale representing time, suiting the subject and data; many use a linear scale, in which a unit of distance is equal to a set amount of time.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] This timescale is dependent on the events in the timeline.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] A timeline of evolution can be over millions of years, whereas a timeline for the day of the September 11 attacks can take place over minutes, and that of an explosion over milliseconds.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] While many timelines use a linear timescale—especially where very large or small timespans are relevant -- logarithmic timelines entail a logarithmic scale of time; some "hurry up and wait" chronologies are depicted with zoom lens metaphors.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] More usually, "timeline" refers merely to a data set which could be displayed as described above.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] Time and space are variously intertwined concepts.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] The line is ubiquitous in clocks in the form of a circle, time is spoken of in terms of length, intervals, a before and an after.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] The idea of orderly, segmented time is also represented in almanacs, calendars, charts, graphs, genealogical and evolutionary trees, where the line is central.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] Originally, chronological events were arranged in a mostly textual form.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] This took form in annals, like king lists.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] Alongside them, the table was used like in the Greek tables of Olympiads and Roman lists of consuls and triumphs.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] Annals had little narrative and noted what happened to people, making no distinction between natural and human actions.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] In Europe, from the 4th century, the dominant chronological notation was the table.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] This can be partially credited to Eusebius, who laid out the relations between Jewish, pagan, and Christian histories in parallel columns, culminating in the Roman Empire, according to the Christian view when Christ was born to spread salvation as far as possible.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] His work was widely copied and was among the first printed books.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] This served the idea of Christian world history and providential time.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] The table is easy to produce, append, and read with indices, so it also fit the Renaissance scholars' absorption of a wide variety of sources with its focus on commonalities.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] These uses made the table with years in one column and places of events (kingdoms) on the top the dominant visual structure of time.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] By the 17th century, chronology and geography became the two sources of precise information for European early modern historians.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] In geography, Renaissance mapmakers updated Ptolemy's maps and the map became a symbol of the power of monarchs, and knowledge.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] Likewise, the idea that a singular chronology of world history from contemporary sources is possible affected historians.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] The want for precision in chronology gave rise to historical eclipses in tables, like in the case of Gerardus Mercator.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] Various graphical experiments emerged, from fitting the whole of history on a calendar year to series of historical drawings, in the hopes of making a metaphorical map of time.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] Developments in printing and engraving that made practical larger and more detailed book illustrations allowed these changes, but in the 17th century, the table with some modifications continued to dominate.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] The modern timeline emerged in Joseph Priestley's *A Chart of Biography*, published in 1765.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] It presented dates simply and provided an analogue for the concept of historical progress that was becoming popular in the 18th century.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] However, as Priestley recognized, history is not totally linear.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] The table has the advantage in that it can present many of these intersections and branching paths.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] For Priestley, its main use was a "mechanical help to the knowledge of history", not as an image of history.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] Regardless, the timeline had become very popular during the 18th and 19th centuries.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] Positivism emerged in the 19th century and the development of chronophotography and tree ring analysis made visible time taking place at various speeds.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] This encouraged people to think that events might be truly objectively recorded.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] However, in some cases, filling in a timeline with more data only pushed it towards impracticality.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] Jacques Barbeu-Duborg's 1753 *Chronologie Universelle* was mounted on a 54-feet-long (16½ m) scroll.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] Charles Joseph Minard's 1869 thematic map of casualties of the French army in its Russian campaign put much less focus on the one-directional line.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] Charles Renouvier's 1876 *Uchronie*, a branching map of the history of Europe, depicted both the actual course of history and counterfactual paths.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] At the end of the 19th century, Henri Bergson declared the metaphor of the timeline to be deceiving in *Time and Free Will*.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] The question of big history and deep time engendered estranging forms of the timeline, like in Olaf Stapledon's 1930 work *Last and First Men* where timelines are drawn on scales from the historical to the cosmological.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] Similar techniques are used by the Long Now Foundation, and the difficulties of chronological representation have been presented by visual artists including Francis Picabia, On Kawara, J.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] There are many methods to visualize timelines.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] Historically, timelines were static images and were generally drawn or printed on paper.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] Timelines relied heavily on graphic design, and the ability of the artist to visualize the data.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] Timelines are often used in education to help students and researchers with understanding the order or chronology of historical events and trends for a subject.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] To show time on a specific scale on an axis, a timeline can visualize time lapses between events, durations (such as lifetimes or wars), and the simultaneity or the overlap of spans and events.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] Timelines are particularly useful for studying history, as they convey a sense of change over time.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] Wars and social movements are often shown as timelines.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] Timelines are also useful for biographies.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] Another type of timeline is used for project management.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] Timelines help team members know what milestones need to be achieved and under what time schedule.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] An example is establishing a project timeline in the implementation phase of the life cycle of a computer system.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] Timelines (no longer constrained by previous space and functional limitations) are now digital and interactive, generally created with computer software.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] Microsoft Encarta encyclopedia provided one of the earliest multimedia timelines intended for students and the general public.
[src:timeline-viz/timeline] ChronoZoom is another example of interactive timeline software.
